n* John Would \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(1\u20135, 8\u201310, 12, 13)}}, mixing {{small|(8)}}\n* Fiona Apple \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(5\u20137, 9\u201311, 13)}}\n* [[Dave Way]] \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(7, 9)}}, mixing {{small|(1, 5, 9)}}\n* [[Tchad Blake]] \u2013\u00a0mixing {{small|(2\u20134, 6, 7, 10\u201313)}}\n* [[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013\u00a0mastering\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs master|1719775}}\n*{{Musicbrainz release group|a9ee533f-8871-4f62-a6bb-91eb264abc90}}\n\n{{Fiona Apple}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Sebastian Steinberg]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded in a home studio]]\n[[Category:Epic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Fiona Apple albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| cover        = Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters.png\n| alt          = A black-and-white close-up of Apple with a very thick black border that has hand-drawn lightning bolts on either side and the artist and title written in a hand-drawn purple font\n| released     = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n| recorded     = July 2015&nbsp;\u2013 March 2020\n| studio       =\n* Apple's house ([[Los Angeles]])\n* Stanley (Los Angeles)\n* [[Sonic Ranch]] ([[Tornillo, Texas]])\n* [[Dave Way|Waystation]] (Los Angeles)\n| genre        = <!-- Please do not add genres without a reliable source -->\n| length       = 51:54\n| label        = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer     = \n* Fiona Apple\n* Amy Aileen Wood with [[Sebastian Steinberg]]\n* [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| prev_title   = [[The Idler Wheel...]]\n| prev_year    = 2012\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n}}\n\n'''''Fetch the Bolt Cutters''''' is the fifth studio album by American singer-songwriter [[Fiona Apple]]. It was released on April 17, 2020, Apple's first release since ''[[The Idler Wheel...]]'' in 2012. Apple began recording the album in 2015, producing and performing it alongside Amy Aileen Wood, [[Sebastian Steinberg]] and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]. It features a percussive and idiosyncratic sound, lyrically exploring freedom from impression and Apple's relationships with women. The album received universal critical acclaim upon its release, and is currenty the highest-rated album on review aggregator [[Metacritic]].\n\n==Background and recording==\nIn 2012, Apple began conceptualising a new album, considering a [[concept album]] based on her home in [[Venice Beach]] or the [[Pando (tree)|Pando]] in Utah.\n\nIn February 2015, she began rehearsals for the album with band members [[Sebastian Steinberg]], Amy Aileen Wood and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]].<ref name=\"VultureProfile\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters.html|title=Allow Fiona Apple to Reintroduce Herself|last=Handler|first=Rachel|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> They began writing and rehearsing in Apple's [[Venice Beach]] home studio, using home-made percussive objects and chanting as they marched around the house.<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/03/23/fiona-apples-art-of-radical-sensitivity|title=Fiona Apple's Art of Radical Sensitivity|last=Nussbaum|first=Emily|author-link=Emily Nussbaum|website=[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July, they began recording the album, spending three weeks at the [[Sonic Ranch]] studio in rural Texas, with little success. A few months later, after returning to Venice Beach, they began making progress, with Apple recording long takes consisting of instruments being hit against surfaces and objects. Apple's vocals were unedited, and the album developed a highly percussive sound.<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/><ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\nBy July 2019, Apple had begun mixing the album. In September, the process began to slow down, with Apple developing doubts about the album.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> At this time, the artist first mentioned work on her new project in an interview with ''[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]'', explaining that she was still working hard on her next album which should have been released \"a million years ago\" and was hoping to put it out in 2020. She also admitted to being reclusive due to ongoing recording sessions at her Venice Beach house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/fiona-apple-is-still-calling-bullshit.html|title=Fiona Apple Is Still Calling Bullshit|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, she played the mixes to her band members, whose positive response brought Apple back on track.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> In an interview that month, she said that the album process was in its final stages, with the only things left being \"artwork and stuff\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-soon/|title=Fiona Apple says new album will \"be done soon\"|last=Bacior|first=Robin|website=Consequence of Sound|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-updates.html|title=15 Minutes With Fiona Apple|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=Vulture|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, 2020, she revealed that she had finished recording.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/fiona-apple-reveals-her-new-album-is-finished-2622233|title=Fiona Apple reveals her new album is finished|last=Langford|first=Jackson|website=[[NME]]|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n===Musical style===\nThe album's sound is defined by percussion. Apple's characteristic piano-playing is still evident, but takes a more percussive form.<ref name=\"NYTReview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/17/arts/music/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters.html|title=Fiona Apple Is Back and Unbound: Let\u2019s Discuss|last1=Pareles|first1=Jon|author-link1=Jon Pareles|last2=Caramanica|first2=Jon|author-link2=Jon Caramanica|last3=Morris|first3=Wesley|author-link3=Wesley Morris|last4=Zoladz|first4=Lindsay|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Stereogum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2081382/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review/franchises/premature-evaluation/|title=Premature Evaluation: Fiona Apple ''Fetch The Bolt Cutters''|last=Breihan|first=Tom|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Stereogum]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> As well as drum sets and traditional percussion, the album features the use of found objects as percussion, such as a metal butterfly and the bones of Apple's dog Janet.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/><ref name=\"Credits\"/> The experimental rhythms on the album evoke [[industrial music]] and are juxtaposed against more traditional melodies.<ref name=\"LA Times\"/> ''[[Stereogum]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Tom Breihan argues that while percussive music is typically \"built around the idea of dancing, of guiding and channeling the rhythms of the human body\", the album instead \"plays as a wild, feverish attempt to mirror the chaos that goes on in the human mind when it\u2019s at its most overheated\"<ref name=\"Stereogum\"/>\n\nThe album often rejects [[popular music]]'s traditional verse-chorus structure. The unpredictable songs feature looped sections, sudden stops and tempo changes.<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/><ref name=\"LA Times\"/><ref name=\"newyorker\"/> Apple's long-time bassist [[Sebastian Steinberg]] compared the album to Apple's 2012 song \"Hot Knife\", describing it as \"very raw and unslick\".<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> It has been noted as less melancholy than Apple's past work, with the uptempo songs being described as \"funny, angry, and at times triumphant\".<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/> The album features frequent improvisation, as well as background noise such as the barking of dogs, largely as a result of its home recording. Apple's dog Mercy appears on the album, as well as [[Cara Delevigne]]'s Leo and Alfie, and Zelda Hallman's Maddie.<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/>\n\nOn the album, Apple approached her voice as a musical instrument, commenting: \"I have fun with my voice, but I\u2019m not trying to make it pretty all the time. I\u2019m not trying to convince anybody I\u2019m a singer. It just turned out to be another instrument\".<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/> Breihan noted that Apple demonstrates \"a [[rapper]]\u2019s sense that words can be music\",<ref name=\"Stereogum\"/> while ''[[The Guardian]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Laura Barton]] highlighted the intimacy of Apple's vocals: \"half-conversational, half-self-mutters, allowing every scuff, breath and feral yelp\".<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> [[Jon Pareles]] and [[Wesley Morris]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' found that \"whether she\u2019s cooing with sarcastic solicitousness or rasping close to a scream, she articulates every word clearly, emoting but never losing control\".<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/>\n\nThe album defies genre categorisation, and critics have noted its originality.<ref name=\"Stereogum\"/><ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Nevertheless, it has been compared to the works of [[Joni Mitchell]],<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/><ref name=\"Observer\"/> [[Tom Waits]],<ref name=\"The Times\"/><ref name=\"NYTReview\"/><ref name=\"Observer\"/> [[Nina Simone]],<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/><ref name=\"LA Times\"/> and [[Kate Bush]],<ref name=\"The Times\"/><ref name=\"NYTReview\"/> who is quoted on the title track.<ref name=\"Observer\"/>\n\n===Lyrics===\nLyrically, Apple identified the album's main theme as \"not being afraid to speak,\"<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> with Barton similarly recognising \"a refusal to be silenced\".<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Apple later said that this was an oversimplification, elaborating that \"it's about breaking out of whatever prison you\u2019ve allowed yourself to live in,\" and pinpointing the message as: \"Fetch the fucking bolt cutters and get yourself out of the situation you\u2019re in\".<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/> Pareles found that the album explored \"both past and present injuries: bullying, sexual assault, destructive mind games, romantic debacles, [Apple's] own fears and compulsions and the people who have taken advantage of them\".<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/> The album explores freedom,<ref name=\"Observer\"/> with Breihan writing that \"we can hear the euphoria of a great unburdening\".<ref name=\"Stereogum\"/> The album has also been identified as Apple's most humorous album.<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/>\n\nAnother theme Apple explores on the album are her complex social relationships with other women.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> Apple commented that these relationships began to suffer in middle school,<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/> and the album features Apple trying to make peace \"the sorts of women that society has always deemed her 'competition'\", such as subsequent girlfriends of her exes.<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/> Apple summarised this idea as \"not letting men pit us against each other or keep us separate from each other so they can control the message\".<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/>\n\n\n==Release==\nOn March 16, 2020, Apple announced the album and its title in an extensive ''[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]'' profile.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> At the start of April, she announced that the album was set to be released digitally on April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-releasing-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-this-month/|title=Fiona Apple Releasing New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' This Month|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 1, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Epic Records]] had planned to release the album in October, due to promotional limitations brought by the [[impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage|coronavirus pandemic]]. However, Apple pushed to release the album early, both for the benefit of listeners who were under [[self-isolation]], and so she could avoid stressful press commitments.<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/> Critics have commented on the timeliness of releasing the album during the pandemic, finding thematic relevance in its exploration of confinement, and comparing Apple's reclusiveness to the widespread self-isolation restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-album-of-the-pandemic.html|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' Is the Unofficial Album of the Pandemic|last=Adams|first=Sam|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review/610051/|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s Survival Guide to Isolation|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Boston Globe\"/>\n\n=== Artwork and title ===\nThe album's artwork was designed by band member [[Dav\u00edd Garza]], following the decision to release the album early. Apple sent him a photo she had taken of herself \"two or three\" years earlier, and saved as a potential cover photo. On the choice of photograph, she commented: \"That face is very much me. I just wanted to be like, 'Hey, guess what? I\u2019m back! Here are some songs. Want to listen to the music, huh? Hi, hi, hi, hi.'\"<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/>\n\nThe title, ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'', is a quote from the British-Irish crime drama television series ''[[The Fall (TV series)|The Fall]]'', where the protagonist, a sex-crimes investigator portrayed by [[Gillian Anderson]], recites the phrase while investigating a crime scene where a woman was tortured.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| AOTY = 95/100<ref name=\"aoty\">{{cite web |title=Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters - Reviews |url=https://www.albumoftheyear.org/album/224348-fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters.php |publisher=Album of The Year |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| ADM = 9.1/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web |title=Fetch The Bolt Cutters by Fiona Apple reviews|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/11368/Fiona-Apple-Fetch-The-Bolt-Cutters.aspx |publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC = 100/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/fetch-the-bolt-cutters/fiona-apple|title=Fetch the Bolt Cutters by Fiona Apple Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev1score = A<ref name=\"The A.V. Club\">{{cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/with-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-fiona-apple-hits-a-zenith-1842908893|title=With Fetch The Bolt Cutters, Fiona Apple hits a zenith of liberation and experimentation|last=Corcoran|first=Nina|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = A<ref>{{cite web |last1=Monokandilos |first1=Irene |title=Album Review: Fiona Apple's Fetch the Bolt Cutters Is an Untethered Masterpiece |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/04/album-review-fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/17/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 a glorious eruption|last=Barton|first=Laura|author-link=Laura Barton|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev4score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-new-album-tracklist-stream-a9468761.html|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: A witty, wonderful album laced with defiance|last=Pollard|first=Alexandra|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"The Irish Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-a-bracing-collection-1.4228651|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 A bracing collection|last=Clayton-Lea|first=Tony|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Irish Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-2648715|title=Fiona Apple \u2013 \u2018Fetch The Bolt Cutters\u2019 review: an intoxicating listen that will cut deep|last=Krol|first=Charlotte|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[NME]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[The Observer]]''\n| rev7score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Observer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/18/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-fourth-album-strange-exceptional|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 a strange, exceptional record|last=Empire|first=Kitty|author-link=Kitty Empire|date=April 18, 2020|website=[[The Observer]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev8score = 10/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters Album Review|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-2-984926/|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s \u2018Fetch the Bolt Cutters\u2019 Is a Triumphant Statement of Self-Discovery and Solidarity\n|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''\n| rev10score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-proof-one-greatest-songwriters/|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: a masterpiece for the #MeToo era|last=McCormick|first=Neil|author-link=Neil McCormick|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev11 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev11score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-she-has-kate-bushs-poetry-and-the-spirit-of-tom-waits-j088600fq/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2014 she has Kate Bush\u2019s poetry and the spirit of Tom Waits|last=Hodgkinson|first=Will|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' was met with widespread acclaim, with many critics deeming it an instant classic, a masterpiece, and Apple's best work to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-roundup.html|title=Critics Agree: Fiona Apple\u2019s ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' Is an Instant Classic|last=Curto|first=Justin|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> At review aggregator [[Metacritic]], the release received a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 100 out of 100, based on 17 reviews,<ref name=\"MC\" /> making it the highest-rated non-retrospective album in the website's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/browse/albums/score/metascore/all/filtered?sort=desc|title=Best Music and Albums of All Time|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> It is also the second highest-rated album on [[AnyDecentMusic?]], with a rating of 9.1/10.<ref name=\"adm\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/chart/AllTime.aspx|title=All Time|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> [[Album of the Year (website)|Album of the Year]] assigned it a 95 out of 100.<ref name=\"aoty\" />\n\nThe album was awarded ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'''s  first perfect score since [[Kanye West]]'s ''[[My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy]]'' in 2010, with Jenn Pelly writing, \"No music has ever sounded quite like it.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/fiona-apples-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-scores-a-10-on-pitchfork/ |title=Pitchfork gives Fiona Apple's new album a 10 |last=Hatfield |first=Amanda |date=April 17, 2020 |website=[[BrooklynVegan]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/pitchfork-fiona-apple-first-perfect-score-decade/ |title=Pitchfork just gave Fiona Apple their first perfect score in almost a decade |last=Jenke |first=Brittany |date=April 17, 2020 |website=Tone Deaf |publisher=The Brag |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> [[Neil McCormick]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' described it as \"a masterpiece for the [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]] era\", writing that it \"feels about as real as music can be\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> [[Laura Barton]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented on the album's \"refusal to be silenced\", writing: \"The result is that this seems not so much an album as a sudden glorious eruption; after eight long years, an urgent desire to be heard\".<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Mikael Wood of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote of the \"stunning intimacy of the material here\u2014a rich text to scour\", adding \"you'd need to go back to the later parts of [[Nina Simone]]\u2019s catalog to find another pop vocalist as eager as Apple is to make such a show of unprettiness.\"<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-04-16/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s stunningly intimate new album makes a bold show of unprettiness|last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Judy Berman of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' similarly praised the album for its \"conversational tone, manifested in Apple\u2019s talky delivery as well as in lyrics that scan as prose more often than poetry, [which] creates a rare intimacy\", and commented that \"As beautiful as the melodies and the epiphanies they carry often are, the songs are not what you would call \u2018pretty.\u2019...Yet ''Bolt Cutters''\u00a0wouldn\u2019t be the extraordinary experiment in aural and lyrical honesty that it is if it sounded too polished\".<ref name=\"Time Magazine\">{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5823031/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review/|title=Fetch the Bolt Cutters Is Raw, Introspective and Everything We Need Out of a Fiona Apple Album|last=Berman|first=Judy|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Maura Johnston]] of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' applauded the album for its \"matter-of-fact depictions of everyday brutality\", and added that \"even [during] the most intense moments of ''Fetch,'' her lyrics retain a playfulness that acts as a ballast.\" She also commended Apple's \"husky [[alto]]\", which \"remains the focal point, launching into melodies that are instantly sticky as effortlessly as it engages in tensely rhythmic ''[[Sprechstimme]]''.\"<ref name=\"Boston Globe\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/16/arts/fiona-apple-makes-defiance-sound-exhilarating-fetch-bolt-cutters/|title=Fiona Apple makes defiance sound exhilarating on \u2018Fetch the Bolt Cutters\u2019|last=Johnston|first=Maura|author-link=Maura Johnston|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Boston Globe]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> ''[[The Observer]]'''s [[Kitty Empire]] described the album as \"a strange and exceptional record, even within the context of an uncommon career\".<ref name=\"Observer\"/> Patrick Ryan of ''[[USA Today]]'' wrote the album \"simmers with defiance, dark wit and quiet rage\", describing it as \"a dense and richly poetic\u00a0masterpiece from one of music's best modern storytellers\" with \"razor-sharp statements and evocative lyrics that reveal themselves in every new listen\".<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/04/17/fetch-bolt-cutters-review-fiona-apple/5128604002/|title=Album review: Fiona Apple's 'Fetch the Bolt Cutters' is a blistering, emotional triumph|last=Ryan|first=Patrick|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[USA Today]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|headline = ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' track listing\n| all_writing = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| title1 = I Want You to Love Me\n| length1 = 3:57\n| title2 = Shameika\n| length2 = 4:08\n| title3 = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| length3 = 4:58\n| title4 = Under the Table\n| length4 = 3:21\n| title5 = Relay\n| length5 = 4:49\n| title6 = Rack of His\n| length6 = 3:42\n| title7 = Newspaper\n| length7 = 5:32\n| title8 = Ladies\n| note8 = music composed by [[Sebastian Steinberg]] and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| length8 = 5:25\n| title9 = Heavy Balloon\n| length9 = 3:26\n| title10 = Cosmonauts\n| length10 = 3:59\n| title11 = For Her\n| length11 = 2:43\n| title12 = Drumset\n| length12 = 2:40\n| title13 = On I Go\n| length13 = 3:09\n| total_length = 51:59\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''.<ref name=\"Credits\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-shares-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-listen-and-read-the-full-credits/|title=Fiona Apple Shares New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'': Listen and Read the Full Credits|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Band'''\n* [[Fiona Apple]] \u2013\u00a0vocals {{small|(all tracks)}}, piano {{small|(1, 2, 4, 9, 10)}}, [[Casio]] drums {{small|(1)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 3, 5\u20137, 9, 10, 13)}}, background vocals {{small|(2\u20135, 7\u201313)}}, drums {{small|(3, 5\u20137, 9, 11, 13)}}, metal butterfly {{small|(3)}}, [[Mellotron]] {{small|(6, 12)}}, electronic drums {{small|(7)}}, timpani {{small|(7)}}, [[Wurlitzer electric piano|Wurlitzer]] {{small|(8)}}, Casio {{small|(9)}}, bells {{small|(9)}}, chair {{small|(12)}}\n* [[Sebastian Steinberg]] \u2013\u00a0bass {{small|(1\u201310, 12, 13)}}, drums {{small|(1)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 5, 9)}}, [[Autoharp#Electric autoharp|electric autoharp]] {{small|(10, 13)}}, acoustic 12-string guitar {{small|(10)}}, slide guitar {{small|(10)}}, background vocals {{small|(12)}}, lighter on Wurlitzer {{small|(12)}}, harp {{small|(12)}}, watertower {{small|(13)}}, stomps {{small|(13)}}, breathing {{small|(13)}}\n* Amy Aileen Wood \u2013 drums {{small|(1\u201310, 12, 13)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 4, 5, 9, 10, 13)}}, loops {{small|(10)}}\n* [[Dav\u00edd Garza]] \u2013\u00a0[[vibraphone|vibes]] {{small|(4, 8)}}, percussion {{small|(5, 8, 9, 12, 13)}}, guitar {{small|(6, 7)}}, background vocals {{small|(8, 12)}}, Mellotron {{small|(8)}}, electric guitar {{small|(10)}}, Wurlitzer {{small|(10)}}, organ {{small|(12)}}, watertower {{small|(13)}}\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n{{div col}}\n* [[Best Coast|Bobb Bruno]] \u2013\u00a0special effects {{small|(