eries)|Mistresses]]'' || Elderly Patient || Episode: \"Rebuild\"\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Modern Family]]'' || Marty || Episode: \"[[Playdates (Modern Family)|Playdates]]\"\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[The Guest Book]]'' || Edgar || Episode: \"Story Eight\"\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]'' || Howard || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Another Period]]'' || Laverne Fusselforth V || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Teachers (2016 TV series)|Teachers]]'' || Jerry || Episode: \"Dosey Don't\"\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Superstore (TV series)|Superstore]]'' || Dr. Fogler || Episode: \"Delivery Day\"\n|-\n| 2020 || ''[[Grace and Frankie]]'' || Bruno || Episode: \"The Scent\"\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n! {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n|1962 || [[Tony Awards]] || Best Supporting Actor || ''[[Subways Are for Sleeping]]'' || {{nom}}  ||<ref name=\"Saad\" />\n|-\n|1964 || [[Obie Award]] || Distinguished Plays and Best Music|| ''[[Home Movies (musical)|Home Movies]]''|| {{win}} ||{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n|-\n|1979 || [[Grammy Awards]] || [[Grammy Award for Best Children's Album|Best Recording for Children]] || ''[[The Hobbit (1977 film)|The Hobbit]]'' || {{nom}} ||{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n|-\n|2000 || [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] || [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Cast in a Motion Picture]] || ''[[Being John Malkovich]]'' || {{nom}} ||{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Books==\n* {{cite book |title=Me and the Orgone |location=Princeton, N.J |publisher=American College of Orgonomy Press |year=1972 |isbn=0-9679670-1-5|title-link=Me and the Orgone }}\n* {{cite book |title=Too Much Is Not Enough |location=Secaucus, N.J |publisher=L. Stuart |year=1988 |isbn=0-8184-0465-5}}\n* {{cite book |title=25 Ways to Cook a Mouse for the Gourmet Cat |location=Secaucus, N.J |publisher=Carol Publishing Group |year= 1994 |type=Print |isbn=1-55972-199-5}}\n* {{cite book |title=M@il for Mikey: an odd sort of recovery memoir |type=Hardcover |publisher=[[Barricade Books]] |edition=1st |date=September 3, 2008 |location=Fort Lee, New Jersey |isbn=978-1569803509 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/mailformikeyodds0000bean }}\n\n==Recordings==\n* ''At the Hungry'' (1959 Fantasy UFAN 7009), comedy\n* ''You're A Good Man, Charlie Brown'' (as Charlie Brown, 1966), comedy<ref name=\"Gesner\" />\n* ''I Ate the Baloney'' (1969 Columbia CS 9743), comedy\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|0004730}}\n* {{TCMDb name|12043}}\n* {{IBDB name|31376}}\n* {{Iobdb name|16222}}\n* {{findagrave|206909065}}\n* {{AllMovie name|4757}}\n* {{Discogs artist|1564216}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes person | orson_bean}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bean, Orson}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Vermont]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in California]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:Hollywood blacklist]]\n[[Category:Orgonomy]]\n[[Category:Writers from Burlington, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Vermont]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Vermont]]\n[[Category:Cambridge Rindge and Latin School alumni]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Coolidge family]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Orson Bean\n| image        = Orson Bean 1965.JPG\n| caption      = Bean in 1965\n| birth_name   = Dallas Frederick Burrows\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1928|07|22}}\n| birth_place  = [[Burlington, Vermont]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|02|07|1928|07|22}}\n| death_place  = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| death_cause  = [[Single-vehicle crash|Single-vehicle collision]]\n| occupation   = Actor, comedian, writer, producer\n| children     = 4\n| years_active = 1952\u20132020\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Jacqueline de Sibour|1956|1962|end=div.}}<br />{{marriage|Carolyn Maxwell|1965|1981|end=div.}}<br />{{marriage|[[Alley Mills]]|1993}}<ref name=\"McFadden\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/08/arts/orson-bean-dead.html|title=Orson Bean, Free-Spirited Actor of Stage and Screen, Dies at 91|first=Robert D.|last=McFadden|date=February 8, 2020|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Orson Bean The Twilight Zone.jpg|thumb|<center>[[William Schallert]] and Orson Bean in \"[[Mr. Bevis]]\", a 1960 episode of<br />''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]''</center>]]\n\n'''Orson Bean''' (born '''Dallas Frederick Burrows'''; July 22, 1928&nbsp;\u2013 February 7, 2020) was a veteran American film, television, and stage actor, and a comedian, writer, and producer.  He was a game show and talk show host<ref name=\"McFadden\" /><ref name=\"Saad\" /><ref name=\"Hollywood\">{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/orson-bean-dead-dr-quinn-actor-was-91-1000269 |first1=Mike |last1=Barnes |first2=Duane |last2=Byrge |work=[[Hollywood Reporter]]|title=Orson Bean, 'Dr. Quinn' Actor, Dies After Being Struck By Car  |date=February 8, 2020 |accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Haring\">{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/orson-bean-dies-in-traffic-accident-age-91-obituary-1202854627/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|title=Orson Bean Dies: TV, Stage And Film Comedian/Actor/Activist Killed In Accident At Age 91|first1=Bruce |last1=Haring |date=February 8, 2020|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"breaking\" /> and a \"mainstay of Los Angeles\u2019s small theater scene.\"<ref name=\"Saad\" /> He appeared frequently on several televised game shows from the 1960s through the 1980s and was a long-time panelist on the television game show ''[[To Tell the Truth]]''.<ref name=\"Saad\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-orson-bean-2050-story.html |first1=Nardine |last1=Saad |date=February 8, 2020 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |title=OBITUARIES Actor Orson Bean, local theater mainstay who rose to fame as a 1950s TV personality, dies |accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref> \"A storyteller par excellence\",<ref name=\"Haring\" /> he was a favorite of [[Johnny Carson]], appearing on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' over 200 times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmur.com/article/actor-comedian-orson-bean-91-struck-and-killed-by-car-while-walking-in-los-angeles/30822293|title=Authorities: Actor-comedian Orson Bean, 91, struck and killed by car while walking in Los Angeles|last=Press|first=Associated|date=2020-02-08|website=WMUR|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\nBean became one of the first \"neocelebrities\" in television&nbsp;\u2014 someone who was \"famous for being famous.\"<ref name=\"Saad\" />\n\n==Early life==\nOrson Bean was born in [[Burlington, Vermont]] in 1928, while his third cousin twice removed, [[Calvin Coolidge]], was [[President of the United States]].<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/actor-comedian-orson-bean-91-114135652.html|title=Celebrity Actor-comedian Orson Bean, 91, hit and killed by car in LA|date=February 8, 2020|agency=[[Associated Press]]|via=[[Yahoo!]]}}</ref><ref name=\"hr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/orson-bean-talks-new-play-707636|title=Orson Bean Talks New Play, Being Blacklisted in the 1950s (Q&A)|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> Bean was the son of Marian Ainsworth (''n\u00e9e'' Pollard) and George Frederick Burrows. His father was a founding member of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU), a fund-raiser for the [[Scottsboro Boys|Scottsboro Boys']] defense, and a 20-year member of the [[Harvard University Police Department|campus police]] of [[Harvard College]].<ref name=\"Saad\" /><ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/04/15/obituaries/george-burrows-89-an-aclu-founder.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|title=George Burrows, 89, an A.C.L.U. Founder|date=April 15, 1989|access-date=April 10, 2010}}</ref> Bean said his house was \"full of causes\". He left home at 16 after his mother committed suicide.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.smdp.com/beloved-actor-comedian-orson-bean-91-hit-and-killed-by-car-on-venice-blvd/185982|title=Beloved actor-comedian Orson Bean, 91, hit and killed by car on Venice Blvd|date=2020-02-08|work=Santa Monica Daily Press|access-date=2020-02-10|url-status=live|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nBean graduated from Rindge Technical School] in 1946.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alumni Hall Of Fame |url=https://crls.cpsd.us/about_crls/c_r_l_s_reunions/alumni_hall_of_fame |website=crls.cpsd.us |access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> He then joined the United States Army<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/actor-comedian-army-vet-orson-bean-91-hit-and-killed-by-car-in-la-1.618054|title=Actor-comedian, Army vet Orson Bean, 91, hit and killed by car in LA|website=Stars and Stripes}}</ref> and was stationed in [[Japan]] for a year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Classic Hollywood: Orson Bean, a sage on the Geffen stage |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-ca-classic-hollywood-20140518-story.html |access-date=February 8, 2020 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 17, 2014}}</ref> Following his military service, Bean began working in small venues as a stage magician before transitioning in the early 1950s to stand-up comedy. He studied theatre at [[HB Studio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbstudio.org/about-hb-studio/alumni/|title=HB Studio \u2013 Notable Alumni &#124; One of the Original Acting Studios in NYC|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Stage name==\nIn an interview on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'' in 1974, Bean recounted the source of his stage name.<ref name=\"Bean Interview\">Interview with Orson Bean, [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=bbX1TA7q_Dw \"Johnny Carson 1974 05 10 Jack Palance\",] ''The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson'', first telecast on [[NBC]] on May 10, 1974; copy of full episode of the late-night talk show posted by Elfreda Arredondo on YouTube, a subsidiary of [[Alphabet Inc.]], Mountain View, California. Retrieved September 30, 2017.</ref> He credited its origin to a piano player named Val at \"Hurley's Log Cabin\", a restaurant and nightclub in Boston, Massachusetts, where he had once performed. According to Bean, every evening before he went on stage at the nightclub, Val would suggest to him a silly name to use when introducing himself to the audience. One night, for example, the piano player suggested \"Roger Duck,\" but the young comedian got very few laughs after using that name in his performance.<ref name=\"Bean Interview\" /> On another night, the musician suggested \"Orson Bean\" and the comedian received a great response from the audience, a reaction so favorable that it resulted in a job offer that same evening from a local theatrical booking agent. Given his success on that occasion, Bean decided to keep using the odd-sounding but memorable name.<ref name=\"Bean Interview\" />\n\nBean claimed that his name was a blend of the pompous and the amusing. He recalled that [[Orson Welles]] once called him over to a table and said \"You stole my name,\" then dismissed him with a wave.<ref name=\"Saad\" />\n\n==Rising comedian==\nIn 1952, Bean made a guest appearance on [[NBC|NBC Radio]]'s weekly hot-jazz series ''[[The Chamber Music Society of Lower Basin Street]]'', giving the young comic his first national exposure. The series, burlesquing stuffy symphonic and operatic broadcasts, had the host (always introduced as a doctor of music) reciting dignified commentary in jazz-musician slang. NBC had broadcast the series off and on since 1940, and it was revived for a 13-week run with \"Dr. Orson Bean\" now as full-time host. Bean's august, bemused delivery belied the fact that this eminent professor was only 24 years old.\n\nFor 10 years, he was the house comic at New York's Blue Angel comedy club.<ref name=\"Saad\" /> In 1954, ''The New York Times'' noted in a review of ''The Blue Angel'', Bean's delivery was always well played, even if a joke fell flat.<ref name=\"breaking\" /> He once hosted a television show \"Blue Angel\" on [[CBS]].<ref name=\"Haring\" /> He \"maintained a steady career since the 1950s and cut his teeth on and off Broadway before becoming a live-television staple.\"<ref name=\"Saad\" />\n\n==Temporary eclipse==\nBean was placed on the [[Hollywood blacklist]] for attending [[Communist Party USA|Communist Party]] meetings while dating a member, but he continued to work through the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name=\"Saad\" /><ref name=\"breaking\" /><ref name=\"hr\" /> \u201cBasically I was blacklisted because I had a cute [[Communism|communist]] girlfriend,\u201d he said in a 2001 interview. He only stopped working in TV for a year.<ref name=\":0\" />  An appearance on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' was cancelled due to his being on the \"black list\" and he was rendered ''persona non grata'' there for years because of it. Sullivan eventually relented and re-booked him, opining that he was the master of his own show, not \"Campbell's Soup\".<ref name=\"Saad\" />\n\n==Theatre==\nOn [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] he starred in the original cast of ''[[Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter? (play)|Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter?]]'' with [[Walter Matthau]] and [[Jayne Mansfield]].<ref name=\"Saad\" /> Then, in 1961, he was featured in ''[[Subways Are for Sleeping]]'' with Sydney Chaplin, for which he received a [[Tony Award]] nomination as [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Featured Actor in a Musical|Best Featured Actor in a Musical]],<ref name=\"Saad\" /><ref name=\"AP\" /> He performed in ''Never Too Late'' the following year. In 1964, he produced the [[Off-Off-Broadway]] musical ''[[Home Movies (musical)|Home Movies]]'' \u2014 which won an [[Obie Award]].<ref name=\"lortel\">[http://www.lortel.org/lla_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&title=Home%20Movies%2F%20Softly%20Consider%20the%20Nearness \" ''Home Movies''/''Softly Consider the Nearness'' Listing\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812210903/http://www.lortel.org/lla_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show |date=August 12, 2014 }} Internet Off-Broadway Database Listing, accessed July 4, 2012</ref><ref name=\"province\">[http://www.provincetownplayhouse.com/plays1960s.html \"Plays Produced in the Provincetown Playhouse in 1960s Chronological\"], ProvincetownPlayhouse.com, accessed July 4, 2012</ref>  And the same year appeared in the Broadway production ''[[I Was Dancing]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff|title=Orson Bean|website=IBDB.com|access-date= April 8, 2018}}</ref>  He starred in the musical \u201cJohn Murray Anderson\u2019s Almanac\u201d.<ref name=\"Saad\" />  He also voiced and sang the role of [[Charlie Brown]] on [[MGM]]'s original 1966 concept album of the musical ''[[You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown]]''<ref name=\"Gesner\">{{cite web |title=You're A Good Man, Charlie Brown [Original concept Album] Clark Gesner|year=1966 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fuKCn9VEN8Y |via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> and starred in ''[[Illya Darling]]'', the 1967 musical adaptation of the film ''[[Never on Sunday]]''.<ref name=\"AP\" />{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nHe was a chief creator and \"mainstay\" of [[Pacific Resident Theatre|The Pacific Resident Theatre]] in Venice, California.<ref name=\"Saad\" /><ref name=\"Haring\" /><ref name=\"breaking\" />\n\n== Television ==\nHe played the title character in the ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|Twilight Zone]]'' episode \"[[Mr. Bevis]]\" (1960) that was an unsuccessful [[television pilot]]<ref>{{Cite book |last=Presnell |first=Don |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MqtTBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA66 |title=A Critical History of Television's The Twilight Zone, 1959-1964 |last2=McGee |first2=Marty |date=2015-07-11 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-1-4766-1038-2}}</ref> For the CBS [[anthology series]] ''[[The DuPont Show with June Allyson]]'',{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} he starred as John Monroe in \"The Secret Life of James Thurber\" (1961), based on the works of the American humorist [[James Thurber]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nAmong dozens of appearances, he starred in ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman]]'', and ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'' while tallying guest appearance credits, e.g., ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'', ''[[Modern Family]]'', ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'', ''[[The Closer]]''.<ref name=\"Saad\" />  Bean was a regular in both ''[[Mary Hartman, Mary Hartman]]''{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} and its spin-off ''[[Fernwood 2Nite]]''. He also portrayed the shrewd businessman and storekeeper Loren Bray on the television series ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman]]'' throughout its six-year run on [[Columbia Broadcasting Company|CBS]] in the 1990s.<ref name=\"AP\" /> He played [[John Goodman]]'s [[homophobia|homophobic]] father on the sitcom ''[[Normal, Ohio]]''. He played the main characters [[Bilbo Baggins|Bilbo]] and [[Frodo Baggins]] in the 1977 and 1980 [[Rankin/Bass]] animated adaptations of [[J.R.R. Tolkien]]'s ''[[The Hobbit (1977 film)|The Hobbit]]'', and ''[[The Return of the King (1980 film)|The Return of the King]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hoffman |first1=Jordan |title=Orson Bean, Legendary Character Actor, Killed in Accident at 91 |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/02/orson-bean-legendary-character-actor-killed-in-accident-at-91 |publisher=Vanity Fair |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=8 February 2020}}</ref> He also played Dr. Lester in [[Spike Jonze]]'s 1999 film, ''[[Being John Malkovich]]''.\n\nBean appeared as a patient in the final two episodes of ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''{{'}}s seventh season in 2003. In 2005, Bean appeared in the sitcom ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'' in an episode titled \"Does This Smell Funny to You?\", playing a former playboy whose conquests included actresses [[Tuesday Weld]] and [[Anne Francis]]. He appeared in the 2007 ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'' episode \"[[Slapsgiving]]\" as [[Robin Scherbatsky]]'s 41-year-old boyfriend, Bob.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} In 2009 he was cast in the recurring role of Roy Bender, a steak salesman, who is [[Karen McCluskey]]'s love interest on the ABC series ''[[Desperate Housewives]]''.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} At the age of 87, Bean in 2016 appeared in \"Playdates\", an episode of the American TV sitcom ''[[Modern Family]]''.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} He appeared in a 2017 episode of ''[[Teachers (2016 TV series)|Teachers]]'' (TV Land, season 2, episode 11, \"Dosey Don't\"). He appeared as the elderly [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] survivor in the 2018 film ''[[The Equalizer 2]]''.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== Game shows ===\nDoing stand-up comedy and magic tricks, and passing on wit and wisdom, he became a regular on ''[[I've Got a Secret]]'', ''[[What\u2019s My Line?]]'', and ''[[To Tell the Truth]]''. He appeared on game shows originating from New York. He was a regular panelist on ''To Tell the Truth''<ref name=McFadden /> in versions from the late 1950s through 1991.<ref name=\"AP\" /> On July 5, 1965, his father appeared as a subject of the panel and he had to disqualify himself from participating.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} He appeared on ''[[Password Plus and Super Password|Super Password]]'' and ''[[Match Game]]'', among other game shows. He hosted a pilot for a revamped version of ''[[Concentration (game show)|Concentration]]'' in 1985,{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} which was picked up in 1987 as ''[[Classic Concentration]]'' with [[Alex Trebek]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== Talk and variety shows ===\nBean was a frequent guest on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' (with both [[Jack Paar]] and [[Johnny Carson]]).<ref name=\"breaking\" /> He guest starred on television talk and variety shows, e.g., [[The Ed Sullivan Show]], [[The Mike Douglas Show]], and [[The Tonight Show starring Johnny Carson]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAn admirer of [[Laurel and Hardy]], Bean, in 1965, served as a founding member of [[The Sons of the Desert]], the international organization devoted to sharing information about the lives of [[Stan Laurel]] and [[Oliver Hardy]] and preserving and enjoying their films.<ref name=\"breaking\">{{cite news|url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/world/actor-orson-bean-dies-in-car-accident-in-los-angeles-980529.html |title=The American actor and comedian Orson Bean has died after being hit by a car in Los Angeles.|publisher=[[BreakingNews.ie]] |date=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966 he helped found the 15th Street School in New York City, a [[primary school]] using the radical democratic free school, [[Summerhill School|Summerhill]], as a model.<ref name=\"breaking\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/lmc1998004805/PP/|title=15th School|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Bean wrote an autobiographical account about his life-changing experience with the [[Orgone|orgone therapy]] developed by [[Austrians|Austrian]]-born psychoanalyst [[Wilhelm Reich]]. Published in 1971, the account is titled ''[[Me and the Orgone|Me and the Orgone: The True Story of One Man's Sexual Awakening]]''.<ref name=\"breaking\" /><ref>{{cite book|title=Me and the Orgone: The True Story of One Man's Sexual Awakening |last=Bean|first=Orson|date=1971|publisher=American College of Orgonomy Press|isbn=978-0967967011}}</ref>\n\nBean was married three times. His first marriage was in 1956 to actress Jacqueline de Sibour, whose stage name was Rain Winslow and who was the daughter of the French [[Nobility|nobleman]] and pilot Vicomte Jacques de Sibour and his wife, Violette B. Selfridge (daughter of American-born British department-store magnate [[Harry Gordon Selfridge]]).<ref name=\"Saad\" /><ref>''Grafic Magazine'', ''[[The Chicago Sunday Tribune]]'', January 25, 1953.</ref><ref>\"Actress Wed to Orson Bean\", ''The New York Times'', August 21, 1956.</ref><ref>\"Frederick T. Bedford Is Dead; Industrialist and Yachtsman, 85\", ''The New York Times'', May 9, 1963.</ref> Before their divorce in 1962, Bean and Jacqueline had one child, Michele.\n\nIn 1965, he married actress and fashion designer Carolyn Maxwell with whom he had three children: Max, Susannah, and Ezekiel.<ref name=\"Saad\" /><ref>\"Designer Will Create Style to Suit Wearer\", ''The New York Times'', April 22, 1964.</ref> The couple divorced in 1981. Their daughter Susannah married journalist [[Andrew Breitbart]] (died 2012) in 1997. Bean's third wife was actress and ''Dr. Quinn'' co-star [[Alley Mills]], 23 years his junior. They married in 1993 and lived in Los Angeles until his death in 2020.<ref name=\"Saad\" />\n\nHe was a \"distant cousin\" of President [[Calvin Coolidge]].<ref name=\"Saad\" /> In later life, \"his politics turned more conservative.\" His daughter married [[Andrew Breitbart]], and Bean authored intermittent columns for ''[[Breitbart News]]''.<ref name=\"Saad\" /><ref name=\"AP\" /> He ventured the thought that being a conservative in 21st-century Hollywood was much like being a suspected [[Communism|Communist]] back in the 1950s.<ref name=\"Saad\" />\n\nWhen his wife Alley Mills was baptized as an adult, he walked with her down to the beach so \"Pastor Ken\" from [[First Lutheran Church of Venice|First Lutheran]] could baptize her in the waters of the Pacific Ocean.<ref name=\"BeanHome\">{{cite book|last1=Bean|first1=Orson|title=Safe At Home|date=2013|publisher=Balboa Press|isbn=978-1452575292|page=221|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8eVkI2QCoPYC&pg=PA221&dq=%22Venice+Beach%22+%22First+Lutheran%22#v=onepage&q=%22Venice%20Beach%22%20%22First%20Lutheran%22&f=false|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>  For many years, Bean and Mills played roles in First Lutheran's annual production of ''[[A Christmas Carol]]''; Bean played [[Ebenezer Scrooge]].<ref name=\"EdwardsVenice\">{{cite news|last1=Edwards|first1=Shane|title=Orson Bean stages a kid-friendly 'Christmas Carol' in Venice|url=http://argonautnews.com/orson-bean-stages-a-kid-friendly-christmas-carol-in-venice/|accessdate=27 November 2017|publisher=The Argonaut|date=9 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor much of his career and to his death, he was represented by the Artists & Representatives agency. In its brief statement after his death, they noted he was an assiduous nurturer of rising talent.<ref name=\"Haring\" />\n\n==Death==\nOn February 7, 2020, while walking near [[Venice Boulevard]] and Shell Avenue in the [[Venice, California|Venice]] section of [[Los Angeles]], Bean was struck by two drivers, with the second vehicle striking him fatally.<ref name=\"Haring\" /> \"The car which was traveling westbound did not see him and clipped him and he went down,\" said [[Los Angeles Police Department]] Captain Brian Wendling. \"A second vehicle's driver was distracted by people trying to slow him down: when the driver looked ahead, a second traffic collision occurred and it caused the death of Bean.\"<ref name=\"McFadden\" /><ref name=\"AP\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://abc7.com/veteran-actor-orson-bean-91-struck-and-killed-by-vehicle-in-venice-friends-say/5912587/|title=Veteran actor Orson Bean, 91, struck and killed by vehicle in Venice, friends say|publisher=[[KABC-TV]]|date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1955 || ''[[How to Be Very, Very Popular]]'' || Toby Marshall ||<ref>[https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/51528 How to be Very Popular] at [[American Film Institute|American Film Institute catalogue]].</ref>\n|-\n| 1959 || ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]'' || Dr. Matthew Smith ||<ref name=\"Saad\" />\n|-\n| 1970 || ''[[Lola (1969 film)|Twinky]]'' || Hal ||\n|-\n| 1977 || ''[[The Hobbit]]'' || Bilbo Baggins ||\n|-\n| 1982 || ''[[Forty Deuce]]'' || Mr. Roper ||\n|-\n| 1987 || ''[[Innerspace]]'' || Lydia's Editor ||\n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[Instant Karma (film)|Instant Karma]]'' || Dr. Berlin ||\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Being John Malkovich]]'' || Dr. Lester ||<ref name=\"Saad\" />\n|-\n| 1999 || ''Unbowed'' || Purdy ||\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Burning Down the House (film)|Burning Down the House]]'' || Sy ||\n|-\n| 2001 || ''The Gristle'' || Mr. Bowen ||\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Frank McKlusky, C.I.]]'' || Mr Gafty ||\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Soccer Dog: European Cup]]'' || Mayor Milton Gallagher ||\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Cacophony'' || Ferruccio || short \n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Alien Autopsy (film)|Alien Autopsy]]'' || Homeless Man ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Mattie Fresno and the Holoflux Universe]]'' || Raff Buddemeyer ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Game of Life (film)|Oranges]]'' || Dennis ||\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[The Equalizer 2]]'' || Sam Rubinstein ||<ref name=\"Saad\" />\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1952 || ''[[Goodyear Television Playhouse]]'' || Performer || Episode: Three Letters \n|-\n| 1952 || ''[[Broadway Television Theatre]]'' || Various || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1952-1956 || ''[[Studio One (American TV series)|Westinghouse Studio One]]'' || Various || 3 episodes\n|-\n| 1954 || ''[[Robert Montgomery Presents]]'' || Performer  || Episode: \"It Happened in Paris\"\n|-\n| 1954\u20131963 || ''[[The